\section{The dm³ Operator Sequence and Contact 3-Manifold}

The generative chain is
\[
G = \underbrace{\text{U}}_{\text{unfolding}} \underbrace{\text{F}}_{\text{fold}} \underbrace{\text{K}}_{\text{curvature}} \underbrace{\text{C}}_{\text{compression}}.
\]
This is realized on a contact 3-manifold \((M, \alpha)\) with Reeb vector field \(R\) satisfying \(\alpha(R) = 1\), \(\iota_R d\alpha = 0\). The contact distribution \(\ker \alpha\) is the 2D plane on which anyonic braiding occurs; the Reeb flow supplies orthogenetic time. The minimal recurrence consistent with the three generative axes is
\[
w(k+3) = w(k+2) + w(k+1) + w(k).
\]

\section{Derivation of the Tribonacci Polynomial and AXLE Weight}

Substitute the geometric ansatz \(w(k) = \eta^{-k}\). The characteristic equation is
\[
\eta^3 - \eta^2 - \eta - 1 = 0,
\]
with dominant real root \(\eta \approx 1.839286755\). The AXLE weight \(\eta^{-k}\) is the topographical measure that makes the geometric Hilbert space and Born rule invariant under the orthogenetic map.

\section{Companion Matrix and Jordan Form}

The recurrence linearizes as \(\mathbf{v}_{k+1} = C \mathbf{v}_k\) with
\[
C = \begin{pmatrix} 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 \\ 1 & 1 & 1 \end{pmatrix}.
\]
Eigenvalues: real dominant \(\lambda_1 = \eta^{-1}\), complex pair with modulus < 1. The matrix is diagonalizable:
\[
C = P J P^{-1}, \quad J = \operatorname{diag}(\lambda_2, \lambda_3, \lambda_1).
\]
The persisting mode \(\eta^{-k}\) is the unique topographical measure after transients decay.

\section{Contact Geometry Backbone}

Local Darboux form: \(\alpha = dz - y\, dx\). The Reeb flow generates orthogenetic time; jet-space extensions lift the structure to nested layers. Normalization against the contact volume \(\alpha \wedge d\alpha\) automatically inserts \(\eta^{-k}\), yielding the geometric Born rule.

\section{Non-Abelian Anyons as Microscopic Realization}

\textbf{Ising anyons} (Moore–Read state): fusion rules
\[
\sigma \times \sigma = 1 + \psi, \quad \sigma \times \psi = \sigma, \quad \psi \times \psi = 1.
\]
Nontrivial F-symbol:
\[
F^\sigma_{\sigma\sigma\sigma} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \begin{pmatrix} 1 & 1 \\ 1 & -1 \end{pmatrix}.
\]
R-symbols: \(R_{\sigma\sigma}^1 = e^{i\pi/8}\), \(R_{\sigma\sigma}^\psi = e^{-i3\pi/8}\). Hexagon equations are satisfied identically.

\textbf{Fibonacci anyons}: fusion \(\tau \times \tau = 1 + \tau\), quantum dimension \(\phi = (1+\sqrt{5})/2\). Braiding is dense in SU(2).

The 2D contact plane hosts anyonic braiding; the Reeb direction supplies orthogenetic time.

\section{Wavenumber 6 and the g-Series Taxonomy}

The orthogenetic recurrence on a contact 3-manifold is 3-step. When the system is placed on a compact azimuthal topology (cylinder or sphere), the only standing-wave modes that can close consistently under the recurrence are Fourier modes \(e^{im\phi}\). The lowest mode that satisfies both the 3-step recurrence and full 2π periodicity with forward/backward symmetry is the azimuthal wavenumber \(m = 2 \times 3 = 6\).

This is the only mathematical derivation possible from the recurrence and topology alone. Wavenumber 6 is therefore the fundamental azimuthal mode selected by the orthogenetic generator on compact azimuthal geometry.

In GTCT-2026-001 the g-series is a taxonomy of behavioral regimes (motivated labels, not derived constants):
\[
g^0 < g^2 < g^6 < g^{33} < g^{64}.
\]
The notation g6:33 is association: the cycle-scale regime g⁶ carries the heuristic stability index 33. The index 33 is combinatorial (ceil(\(\log_2(3!)\times 4\)) = 11, then \(\times 3\) for triple-confirmation robustness) and remains a conjecture for AXLE verification.

\textbf{Note on crystal math (Number 33 paper):} The Saturn north-polar hexagon is an observed six-fold structure. It is consistent with wavenumber 6, but the full atmospheric dynamics that produce it are not derived here from the contact manifold. The observation is empirical; the wavenumber-6 mode is the derived topological consequence of the 3-step recurrence.

